In [16]:
links=['hyderabad','chennai','mumbai','bangalore','delhi','delhi-ncr','pune','gurgaon','noida','ahmedabad','kolkata','lucknow','jaipur','kochi','surat','indore','chandigarh','coimbatore','ghaziabad']
Year=[]
Name = []
Model=[]
Price=[]
KM=[]
location=[]
Fuel=[]
MA=[]
EMI=[]

for i in links:
    url=f'https://www.spinny.com/used-cars-in-{i}/s/'
    driver.get(url)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(driver.page_source, "html.parser")
    #location.append(i)
    
    for i in soup.find_all('div',class_='styles__yearAndMakeAndModelSection'):
        k=i.text
        regex=re.findall('^(\d+)',k)
        if regex:
            Year.append(regex[0])
        else:
            Year.append(np.nan)
   
    for i in soup.find_all('div',class_='styles__yearAndMakeAndModelSection'):
        c=i.text
        try :
            regex=re.findall('\s(\w+)\s\w+',c)
            Name.append(regex[0])
        except:
            Name.append(np.nan)
               
    for i in soup.find_all('div',class_='styles__yearAndMakeAndModelSection'):
        c=i.text
        regex=re.findall('\s\w+\s(\w.+)',c)
        if regex:
            Model.append(regex[0])
        else:
            Model.append(np.nan)
    for i in soup.find_all('li',class_='styles__price'):
        c=i.text
        regex=re.findall('(\d.+)Lakh',c)
        if regex:
            Price.append(regex[0])
        else:
            Price.append(np.nan)
    for i in soup.find_all('li',class_='styles__toOriginalCase'):
        c=i.text
        regex=re.findall('(\d.+)K\skm',c)
        if regex:
            KM.append(regex[0])
        else:
            KM.append(np.nan)
    for i in soup.find_all('li'):
        c=i.text
        regex=re.findall('petrol|diesel',c)
        if regex:
            Fuel.append(regex[0])
    
    for i in soup.find_all('li'):
        c=i.text
        regex=re.findall('manual|automatic',c)
        if regex:
            MA.append(regex[0])

    for i in soup.find_all('li',class_='styles__emiWrap'):
        c=i.text
        regex=re.findall('(\d.+)/m',c)
        if regex:
            EMI.append(regex[0].replace(',',''))
        else:
            EMI.append(np.nan)
    for i in soup.find_all('div',class_='TestDriveAvailability__changeLocationColor'):
        c=i.text
        regex=re.findall('([^ ]+)$',c)
        if regex:
            location.append(regex[0])
        else:
            location.append(np.nan)

Statistical analysis and Visualization¶

Univairate Plots¶

In [96]:
# Histogram of Car Prices using Seaborn
dff = pd.read_csv('spinnycars.csv')
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.histplot(dff['Price(in lakhs)'], bins=20, kde=True, color='skyblue')
plt.title('Distribution of Car Prices')
plt.show()

Interpretation

  • The histogram appears to be right-skewed, indicating that a majority of cars have lower prices, while fewer cars have higher prices. This suggests that most cars in the dataset fall within a relatively affordable price range.
  • The peak of the histogram, also known as the mode, provides insight into the most common price range. It helps identify where the majority of cars are priced.
  • The long right tail of the histogram suggests the presence of some cars with higher prices than the majority. These may be considered as outliers and could represent luxury or high-performance vehicles.
In [97]:
# Pie Chart of Transmission Type Distribution
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 7))
transmission_counts = dff['Auto/manual'].value_counts()
plt.pie(transmission_counts, labels=transmission_counts.index, autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=90)
plt.title('Distribution of Transmission Types')
plt.show()

Interpretation

  • The pie chart shows the proportion of cars with 'Auto' and 'Manual' transmissions.
  • Each slice represents a transmission type, and the size of the slice corresponds to the percentage of cars with that transmission type.
In [98]:
# Bar Plot of Fuel Type Counts
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
sns.countplot(x='Fuel', data=dff)
plt.title('Count of Cars by Fuel Type')
plt.xlabel('Fuel Type')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.show()

Interpretation:

  • The count plot visualizes the distribution of cars based on their fuel types.
  • Each bar represents a different fuel type, and the height of the bar corresponds to the count or frequency of cars with that specific fuel type. Taller bars indicate a higher prevalence of certain fuel types in the dataset.
In [99]:
# Count Plot of Car Years
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.countplot(x='Year', data=dff)
plt.title('Count of Cars by Year')
plt.show()

Interpretation

  • The count plot visualizes the number of cars available for each year.
  • The height of each bar represents the count of cars from a specific manufacturing year.
In [100]:
# KDE Plot of Car Prices
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.histplot(dff['EMI'], fill=True,kde=True)
plt.title('Kernel Density Estimate of EMI')

plt.show()

Interpretation

  • The KDE plot shows the estimated probability density of different EMI values. Higher peaks in the plot indicate regions where EMI values are more concentrated.
  • The central peak or mode represents the most common range of EMI values. Multiple peaks might indicate the presence of different clusters or patterns in the EMI distribution.
  • The width of the KDE plot at different points indicates the variability in EMI values. A wider spread suggests a more diverse range of EMI values.
In [101]:
sns.displot(dff, x ='KM(in 1000s)' )
Out[101]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x221b0e4e250>

Interpretation

  • The histogram displays the distribution of kilometers (in thousands) traveled by the cars in the dataset.
  • The x-axis represents the kilometer values, and the y-axis represents the frequency or count of cars within each kilometer range.
  • Peaks in the histogram indicate common ranges of kilometers traveled. Higher bars suggest that more cars fall within those specific kilometer ranges.
  • Unusually tall bars or isolated bars far from the main distribution might indicate potential outliers.
In [102]:
sns.displot(dff['Brand'])
plt.xticks(rotation=90, ha='right')
plt.show()

Interpretation

  • The histogram shows the distribution of cars among different brands.
  • Each bar represents a unique brand, and the height of the bar corresponds to the count or frequency of cars belonging to that brand.
  • Brands with taller bars indicate that there more common or popular car brands.
  • If there are unusually tall it might indicate outlier brands.

Bivariate Plots¶

In [103]:
# Boxplot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.boxplot(x='Location', y='Price(in lakhs)', data=dff)
plt.title('Box Plot of Car Prices by State')
plt.xlabel('State')
plt.ylabel('Price')
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right') 
plt.show()

Interpretation

  • The box plot represents the distribution of car prices for different states.
  • Each box corresponds to a different state, and the height of the box indicates the interquartile range (IQR) of prices within that state.
  • The horizontal line inside each box represents the median price for cars in that state.
  • The length of the box (IQR) indicate the variability in car prices within each state.
  • Individual points beyond the whiskers represent potential outliers
In [104]:
# Box Plot of Car Prices by Fuel Type
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.boxplot(x='Fuel', y='Price(in lakhs)', data=dff, palette='Set2')
plt.title('Box Plot of Car Prices fuel type')
plt.xlabel('Fuel Type')
plt.ylabel('Price')
plt.show()

Interpretation

  • The box plot visually represents the distribution of car prices for different fuel types.
  • Each box corresponds to a different fuel type, and the height of the box indicates the interquartile range (IQR) of prices within that fuel type.
  • The horizontal line inside each box represents the median price for cars of that fuel type.
  • It provides a measure of central tendency, showing the typical price level for each fuel type.
  • Individual points beyond the whiskers represent potential outliers
In [105]:
sns.catplot(dff,col='Fuel',y='Location',kind='count')
plt.suptitle('Count of Cars by Location and Fuel Type', y=1.02)
plt.show()

Interpretation

  • The categorical plot displays the count of cars in different locations based on their fuel types.
  • Each subplot represents a different fuel type, and the y-axis shows the count of cars in different locations.
  • By comparing the subplots, we can observe how the distribution of cars in different locations varies for each fuel type.

  • Each bar represents a different car brand, and the height of the bar corresponds to the average EMI for that brand.
  • By comparing the heights of the bars, we can observe how the average EMI varies between different car brands.
In [109]:
sns.violinplot(dff,x='Auto/manual',y='Price(in lakhs)')
plt.title('Distribution of Car Prices by Transmission Type')
plt.show()

Interpretation

  • The violin plot displays the distribution of car prices for different transmission types ('Auto/manual').
  • Each violin shape corresponds to a different transmission type, and the width of the shape indicates the density of prices.
  • The horizontal line inside each violin represents the median price for cars of that transmission type.
  • Wider sections indicate more cars in that price range. Narrow sections may indicate fewer cars in that specific price range.
  • By comparing the widths and shapes of the violins, we can assess how the distribution of prices varies between different transmission types.
In [110]:
sns.scatterplot(x='KM(in 1000s)', y='Price(in lakhs)', data=dff)
plt.title('Scatter Plot of Car Prices vs. Kilometers Traveled')
plt.show()

Interpretation

  • The scatter plot visualizes the relationship between the kilometers traveled by cars and their prices.
  • Each point on the plot represents an individual car, with its position determined by the kilometers traveled (x-axis) and the price (y-axis).
  • By observing the general trend of the points, you can identify whether there is a correlation between kilometers traveled and prices.
  • For example, a negative correlation might suggest that cars with more kilometers tend to have lower prices.
In [111]:
sns.lineplot(x='Year', y='Price(in lakhs)', data=dff, marker='o')
plt.title('Line Plot of Car Prices Over the Years')
plt.show()

Interpretation

  • The line plot visualizes how car prices change over different years.
  • Each point on the line represents the average price of cars in a specific year.
  • By observing the trend of the line, you can identify whether there is an overall increase, decrease, or stability in car prices over the years.
  • Fluctuations in the line indicate variations in car prices from year to year.

Multivariate Plots¶

In [112]:
sns.jointplot(x='KM(in 1000s)', y='Price(in lakhs)',hue='Fuel', data=dff)
plt.suptitle('Joint Plot of Car Prices vs. Kilometers Traveled by Fuel Type', y=1.02)
plt.show()

Interpretation

  • The joint plot combines scatter plots for kilometers traveled and car prices with different colors indicating different fuel types.
  • It provides a visual representation of the relationship between kilometers traveled, prices, and how these variables vary based on fuel type.
  • The individual scatter plots on the sides show the univariate distribution of kilometers traveled and car prices for each fuel type.
  • The main scatter plot in the center illustrates the bivariate relationship between kilometers and prices, with different colors denoting fuel types.
In [113]:
df2=dff.select_dtypes(include='number')
sns.heatmap(df2.corr(),annot=True)
plt.title('Correlation Heatmap of Numeric Variables')
plt.show()

Interpretation

  • The heatmap visually represents the correlation between numeric variables in the dataset.
  • Each cell in the heatmap corresponds to the correlation coefficient between two variables.
  • The color scale indicates the strength and direction of the correlation. Positive correlations are typically shown in warmer colors (e.g., red), while negative correlations are in cooler colors (e.g., black).
  • High positive values suggest a strong positive correlation, meaning the variables move together.
  • High negative values indicate a strong negative correlation, suggesting an inverse relationship.
  • Values close to zero suggest a weak or no correlation.
In [114]:
sns.pairplot(dff)
plt.suptitle('Pairwise Relationships and Distributions of Variables', y=1.02)
plt.show()

Interpretation

  • The pair plot provides a comprehensive view of the relationships and distributions between all numeric variables in the dataset.
  • Each off-diagonal subplot is a scatterplot showing the relationship between two variables. Help to identify trends and patterns
  • The diagonal subplots show histograms of individual variables, giving insights into their distributions. it also reveal the shape of the distribution for each variable.
In [115]:
sns.displot(df2,bins=40)
plt.title('Distribution of Numeric Variables')
plt.show()

Interpretation

  • The displot displays histograms for each numeric variable in the dataset, providing insights into the distribution of values for each variable.
  • Each subplot represents a different numeric variable, and the height of the bars in the histogram indicates the frequency of values within each bin.
  • The shape of the histograms provides information about the skewness and spread of the distribution for each variable.
In [116]:
sns.stripplot(dff,y='Price(in lakhs)',x='Fuel',hue='Auto/manual')
plt.title('Strip Plot of Car Prices by Fuel Type and Transmission')
plt.show()

Interpretation

  • The strip plot displays individual data points (strips) for car prices, grouped by fuel type and further distinguished by transmission type.
  • Jittering is applied to prevent overlapping of points
  • The dodge parameter separates the strips for different transmission types within each fuel category.
  • The distribution of car prices within each fuel type is visible, and the separation by transmission type allows for comparison of price distributions within each fuel category.

Business porblem analysis¶

Client-1¶

A person wants a car which has travelled less than 50 thousand Kilometers?

Client-2¶

A person wants to buy a second hand car with in a budget of 5 lakhs.suggest cars whose prices are under 5 lakhs

Client-3¶

A person wants to buy a manual diesel car and wants to know the minimum amount of budget he should have

Client-4¶

a person wants to know which brands offer manual cars.

Client-5¶

a person wants to buy a car whose emi is under 9000
